description: Mr. Damm led teams of Systems Engineers that identified, analyzed, and recommended alternatives for system disaster recovery/continuity of operations (COOP) capabilities. He and his SETA (System Engineering, Technical Advisory) and System Integrator contractor teams also drafted a Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) system COOP concept of operations (CONOPS). He regularly applied systems engineering and project planning best practices to transform stakeholder needs into architecture descriptions, inter-operable systems, and software applications. His primary objectives included providing some assurance that the designed or proposed National Technical Means systems would meet or exceed programs' technical specifications and would still comply with national-level requirements. Those funded and non-funded requirements included SIGINT directives, regulations (statutes/laws), and Executive Orders (presidential directives). He regularly briefed findings or delivered point papers to various senior executives and/or senior military officers (“flag” grade). As part of his duties, he analyzed agency information technology and partner information technology (IT) systems and helped in the vetting of possible enterprise (corporate level) and cross-agency information services. He also worked on the planning and source selection phases of various Intelligence Community (IC) system modernization efforts and reviewed the architecture plans of partner agencies. Mr. Damm received awards (from his SIGINT directorate leader, an agency-level director of systems engineering, and the office of the Director of National Intelligence) for his contributions in developing inter-agency initiatives, defining joint solutions, and negotiating common services or compatible/federated information architectures/infrastructures.

title: Senior Information Technology Specialist

description: Mr. Damm analyzed information technology (IT) systems and business processes. During his analyses, he developed system architecture description products for the Business Information Systems modernization portion of the DoD Business Management Modernization Program (BMMP) -- an effort involving over one dozen, disparate Defense agencies. He created DoD Architecture Framework (DoDAF) operational descriptions (OVs) and system descriptions (SVs) and mentored others in the use of software tools and development methodologies. The OV and SV documents included functional data flows, system functional decomposition, operational activity mappings, and business process work flow diagrams. His products were used in the (then) Secretary of Defense's campaign to improve operational effectiveness through process improvement and/or system integration/consolidation. He advised and mentored others on how to utilize architecture modeling tools to create, maintain, and/or enhance the architecture planning process.

description: LtCol Wachter directs ACC's most technically diverse training squadron; leading officers, enlisted, and civilians across 18 AFSCs. LtCol Wachter supervises over 1100 Joint students annually and advises ACC/A3 on status/direction of 15 formal training courses. Additionally, he oversees production & distrobution of operations and safety training videos utilizing a $3.5M state-of-the-art multimedia facility with a $1.1M annual budget. Lt Col Wachter leads ACC/A3's training programs w/global joint impact; flight/weapons/ground safety, Aviation Resource Management, Command & Control, and Aviation Flight Equipment fields.
